A new collection of tantra paintings are now available at Kneeland Co. Rarities. ✨ In November 2011, I was on a flight to New York and opened the NYT to an article about poet Franck André Jamme’s new book, Tantra Song. I became completely enraptured by these round shapes that were so simplistic yet full of depth and color. They had an energy to them and felt like more than just paintings that he discovered in India. In 2013, I bought the book at the LA Art Book Fair and became so obsessed with this type of tantra art (known as yantra) and went on a hunt for every out of print book to educate myself more on the meaning behind these mystical paintings. They originated in the 17th century and most were painted anonymously by Hindu devotees, symbolizing a higher consciousness and used during meditation practice. In 2016, I made my first trip to Delhi which marked the beginning of the most wild adventure in searching for, acquiring, and building a spectacular collection from all over Rajasthan. I’ve spent time with an Indian tantric scholar in California who shared his knowledge and encouraged me to keep building my collection, which I continue to do. Tantra art was the first type of art that felt like a total revelation to me, and it’s so incredibly personal and magical and awe-inspiring when that feeling happens in life. I am so grateful to be able to share and offer these divine works of art. Visit the shop or DM for more information.🪄

3/4 Mexican + 1/4 Irish makes for one reckless combo, but I prefer to think of it as adventurous. This is where my Irish roots come from - my late grandfather, Captain Russell Kneeland, who built this magnificent 86-foot schooner named Princess K’aiulani. She was impeccable, and I’m lucky to have sailed her. I named my business after my grandfather, the father to my amazing mother. He was proud to be Irish and he had one hell of a time exploring the world, sailing the high seas and living it up. This photo of him was taken in Mexico City, after he met my Mexican grandmother. The shell was a treasure he found in Tahiti, and the photos of Princess K’aiulani are from the Nautical Quarterly. Happy St. Patrick’s Day. 🍀

I’ve always been drawn to botanical illustrations and paintings, mostly from India and England. Aside from their obvious beauty, my fascination stems from the idea of being immersed in and connected to nature so deeply that the need to observe and understand flowers, like these heavenly camellias and ornamental bulbs, is completely necessary. I often think about India and the European influence in the floral imagery that came about during the Mughal Empire, how miniature painters were lounging in gardens and creating meticulous works of art that were all dedicated to florals. Later in England, hand colored botanical lithographs became an art form - one that I never get bored by. I discovered these devastatingly gorgeous 19th century lithos while antiquing recently and was completely romanced by the marble trim, gold leaf, and the sublime silk ombré ribbon. These treasures are now available at Kneeland Co. Rarities. Visit the shop or DM for info.✨

This is my incredible grandmother, born in 1933 in Guadalajara, Mexico. We called her Birdsel. ❤️ She left the earth peacefully one week ago at the age of 89, and even though I am grateful that I was able to tell her how much I loved her and how wonderful of a grandparent she was, I so wish I could call her and tell her Happy Mother’s Day. She cherished her family and friends and was the confidant of many, and remembered every birthday and special occasion. She was always down for a good time and no one loved to dance more than she did. The empathy she had for others was admirable as was her kindness, the epitome of elegance and grace. She was the mother to my amazing mama. She taught me about the importance of tenacity and hard work, having goals, and helped me to see the world through a bigger lens. She introduced me to design, good food, and the ballet. She was my #1 fan, always supportive of my grand dreams and full life. It’s heartbreaking to think about her not being able to see a new chapter of my life unfold, but I’m lucky that I had her for as long as I did. There is nothing quite like the unconditional love of a grandmother. ❤️

My favorite feature on our new website is Shop by Country - a filtered search that allows you to see an ebullient mix of craftsmanship from some of my most frequented and beloved places around the world - including the US. This photo really captures my deep appreciation for the hand made, from the pottery by @caradeplanta that is made in Cuernavaca and Mexico City, to the pineapples from Michoacán, to the @seanginceramics made in LA, to the old tantra painting from Jaipur - all against a backdrop of Sintra wallpaper from @sisterparishdesign - one of the most iconic brands that has always championed craftsmanship and the work of the hand.✨ 
📷/styling/flowers by @amykchin

When I was searching for the perfect spot in 2019 to expand the textile studio and open a store, the first thing that came to mind was that I wanted to be a destination rather than be in the hub of LA. I explored West Adams because I was fascinated by the history of the neighborhood, and when I spotted an empty blue storefront next to the record shop @highfidelityla I jumped on it. I’ve always wanted to be next door to a record shop. I started with a blank slate and picked a wallpaper as a starting point: the Braquenié Chandernagor from @lamaisonpierrefrey inspired by a 19th century textile document based on the Indian Tree of Life. It was personal to me, having a vintage textile studio and India being one of the great loves of my life. The small kitchen came next, built by my good friend @pop__pop__ who let me choose my favorite oak panels. I didn’t want it to feel too fanciful, so I added geometric tiles from Peru. I went psycho finding the perfect shade of purple for the cabinets and went with Benjamin Moore wild orchid. I used bronze pulls by  @ramseyconder and had a custom block-printed fridge curtain made by @gregory_parkinson_surround in India. On the countertop are some of my personal treasures: a vase I commissioned from the lovely @claudiarankin2 who surprised me with a shell, sun, and mermaid as decoration. The coyote is Oaxacan dripware from the 40s I found at a flea market in Mexico City, the marbled dish I picked up in San Miguel de Allende, the woven copper bowl is from my aunt Yvonne Kneeland who works with a community of artisans in Mexico City, the Brutalist-inspired vase is from the great @bzippy who made it for my online store I had about 10 years ago, and the lilac mug was made for Rarities by @mestizmx✨ Nothing fills me up more than being surrounded by soulful, beautiful objects that feel meaningful and are a genuine reflection of the person inhabiting the space. The past year I’ve had the pleasure of bringing in decorative objects, textiles, and artwork for projects to enhance environments and expand the narrative of residential and commercial spaces. It all started here and it’s my jam. ✨
Thank you @amykchin for capturing my world.

The amount of beauty to behold today was completely overwhelming, burned in my memory for life. I spent the day in Etla and went to see the @1050grados exhibition of pottery from all over Oaxaca at CaSa, a former textile factory built in the 19th century. Thank you @christina_hattler_studio for the most magical day filled with so much love and happiness.✨
@marchantastore taking the tile prize, pochote flowers, @lacocinadehumo giving an unforgettable meal, cactus elegante, the pottery corner @piedraderio.oaxaca and Tamayo’s 🍉🍎.

One reason for this visit to Oaxaca was to finally meet the glorious goddess of textiles  @christina_hattler_studio of @mexchic_shop ✨ Christina and I have been orbiting each other for years now, and I have always been amazed and inspired by the work she is doing with natural dyes and fibers. I visited her store in Oaxaca City and her studio in Santa María del Tule, and completely lost my mind over her beautiful process of designing and making clothing and home goods by hand. Her clothes are perfectly cut in silhouettes that are timeless and sensual, and her new one-of-a-kind silk pleated pieces are completely out of this world. Clothing, tabletop textiles, and blankets are thoughtfully made and dyed in her studio with plants from her garden. She is immensely talented, wildly creative, and I’m so excited to bring her work to Kneeland Co. Rarities. The home collection will be available soon, and next Spring we will be introducing her  one-of-a-kind pieces of clothing as well as my favorites from her classic collection.💫
I’m so psyched that I got to experience this awe-inspiring exhibition by textile master Román Gutiérrez Ruiz @cato.oax @miku_meko_oaxaca ✨ Totally floored.

Until next time 🇲🇽✌🏽

I Am Also The Snake by @jo_skum 🐍⚡️🐍

I am so psyched for this!

Growing up in the Midwest, Joanna Skumanich was heavily influenced by her grandmother who was a seamstress and collector of fabrics and notions, which led her to begin her embroidery practice in 2013 after working as an illustrator. Weaving the symbolism of her childhood with tactile craft to create fantastical quilts and tapestries exploding with texture and color, Joanna combines embellishments; paint; and textiles to articulate her memories through portraits and scenes that are both personal and imaginative. This exhibition is an exploration of nostalgia, storytelling, and tradition.💫

Family Portrait by @jo_skum 🍦

I can’t get enough of this quilt. Every time I look at it, I see something entirely new and really feel how personal it is. The legs with a batik wax print and single stitch finished with leather Mary Janes totally slays me, as does the triple threat ice cream with melting mint chocolate chip. Every. single. piece. was hand sewn and embroidered. It is a textile narrative brimming with the beautiful chaos of childhood. 🎶

“Ayahuasca plays a pivotal role in my culture, serving as a powerful means of healing the afflicted. This sacred wisdom often manifests as vivid visions.” 🐍

Lastenia Canayo is an artist from the Shipibo-Konibo indigenous community on the banks of the Ucayali River in the Peruvian Amazon. Her name in her native language is ‘Pecon Quena’, which translates to “the one who calls the colors.” This incredible work conveys the ancestral knowledge and understanding of her environment, representing the protective spirit within each plant and animal that safeguards the rainforest as a way to maintain the divine connection between humans and nature.✨ I’m so psyched to have these paintings available at Kneeland Co. Rarities. Visit the shop or DM for info.

The first time I visited @thegempalace in Jaipur, these are the jewels that put a spell on me: amethyst, emerald, and 22K gold floral earrings. They were some of the first designs to come out of the storied jeweler many years ago, and I appreciated how meticulously carved they were - made by hand in their workshop that sits inside the store, walls covered in Indian paisleys decorated with photos of Maharajas and Maharanis. When I was preparing to open Rarities, I knew I wanted them to live here and be a symbol of the admiration and deep love I have for India - a place of seduction, tenderness, and endless wonder. I spent an entire afternoon at The Gem Palace putting together a collection and am so happy to carry these stunning treasures. A selection of Gem Palace earrings are online and at the shop.✨
